value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects the organization of the actin cytoskeleton. Actin cytoskeleton organization results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments and associated proteins.

definition.value: Consider annotating to 'abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology' (FYPO:0000350), but note that an abnormal cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal cytoskeleton morphology.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects the organization of the microtubule cytoskeleton. Microtubule cytoskeleton organization results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and associated proteins.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype that affects a response to a stimulus.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A phenotype that affects a biological process.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A biological process phenotype that affects conjugation.
A conjugation phenotype in which a cell's response to mating pheromone is abnormal.
A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population undergoes conjugation.

definition.value: Note that this term refers specifically to conjugation, whereas experiments that measure mating efficiency often do so by counting zygotes plus asci, sometimes also including spores. For such experiments, we recommend using 'decreased mating efficiency' (FYPO:0000708).

label.value: sensitive to stress during vegetative growth

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to a stress. Typically, a cell population is deemed sensitive to a stress if cells in the population stop growing (and may die) when exposed to the stress at an intensity that allows a population of wild type cells to grow and divide.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to a stress in culture. If you have assayed the response to the stress at the subcellular or molecular level, consider annotating to 'abnormal cellular response to stress during vegetative growth' (FYPO:0001341).

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which spore germination is abnormal.
A viability phenotype in which a spore is unable to survive under conditions in which wild type spores survive, and is smaller than normal. An inviable spore does not germinate.

A viability phenotype in which a spore is unable to survive under conditions in which wild type spores survive, and has an abnormal morphology (i.e. size, shape, or structure). An inviable spore does not germinate.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, with normal germ tube morphology

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a normal germ tube, but does not go on to form a viable dividing cell.

label.value: inviable after spore germination with normal, unseptated germ tube morphology

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a normal germ tube, but does not septate or go on to form a viable dividing cell.

label.value: inviable after spore germination with normal, septated germ tube morphology

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a normal germ tube, and undergoes septation, but does not go on to form a viable dividing cell.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, with abnormal germ tube morphology

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a germ tube with abnormal morphology (i.e. size, shape, or structure), and does not go on to form a viable dividing cell.

label.value: inviable after spore germination with elongated germ tube

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce an elongated germ tube, and does not go on to give rise to a viable cell population.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, with elongated, septated germ tube

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce an elongated germ tube, and undergoes septation, but does not go on to form a viable dividing cell.
A viability phenotype in which a spore germinates but fails to produce dividing cells that can survive under normal conditions.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, single cell division, normal cell morphology

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell of normal morphology (i.e. size, shape, and structure) that undergoes a single round of cell division, and then dies.
A cell cycle phenotype in which the onset of anaphase of the mitotic cell cycle begins later than normal.

Often anaphase onset and anaphase B onset are used interchangeably since they are stablished by monitoring cdc13 levels or the switch from phase II to III of spindle elongation. Also, I am not aware of any phenotype where anaphase A starts but anaphase B does not.

label.value: abnormal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore during a mitotic or meiotic nuclear division is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype in which the stable attachment of sister chromatids to microtubules emanating from opposite poles of the mitotic spindle during metaphase plate congression is abnormal.

definition.value: This term is more specific than 'abnormal attachment of mitotic spindle microtubules to kinetochore' (FYPO:0004213) because sister chromatid biorientation normally occurs only as part of metaphase plate congression, not during other stages of mitosis. FYPO:0004213 can be used for abnormal attachment observed at any time during mitosis. Consider also annotating to 'unequal mitotic sister chromatid segregation' (FYPO:0003241) because a problem with biorientation usually results in unequal chromosome segregation.

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of trichostatin A than normal.

label.value: abnormal protein metabolic process during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle that affects protein metabolism in the cell.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein modification during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein modification is abnormal. All modifications may be affected, or only modifications of a certain type, or on specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal histone modification during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle that affects histone modification.

label.value: decreased histone acetylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which histone acetylation occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: increased histone acetylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which histone acetylation occurs to a greater extent than normal.
A cell cycle phenotype in which the G1/S transition of the mitotic cell cycle begins later than normal. The duration of G1 phase is thus longer than normal.

definition.value: A G1/S delay may indicate that a checkpoint, such as the cell size checkpoint or the G1/S DNA damage checkpoint, is activated. Checkpoint activation can be tested using checkpoint kinase mutants.

value.value: A phenotype that affects a process of cellular component organization, i.e. the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a cellular component, that occurs at the cellular level.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which any process of cellular component organization at the cellular level is abnormal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which any process of cellular component assembly at the cellular level is abnormal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitosis is abnormal.
A physical cellular phenotype in which the position or morphology of the mitotic spindle is abnormal.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has a septum in an abnormal location. The normal location is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell. The site of septum assembly is normally determined by the location of the actomyosin contractile ring.

definition.value: Note that the location of the septum is determined by the location of the contractile ring, which in turn is determined by the location of the cell division site, so an abnormality in cell division site determination can be inferred from this phenotype. Consider also annotating to 'mislocalized actomyosin contractile ring' (FYPO:0001369) because if the contractile ring forms in an abnormal location, the septum will also do so.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a single functional copy of a gene does not provide sufficient normal function in a diploid cell.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a single functional copy of a gene provides sufficient normal function in a diploid cell.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of cellular respiration is decreased.

label.value: increased concentration of hydrogen sulfide in growth medium

value.value: A phenotype in which the concentration of hydrogen sulfide released into the growth medium by cells is higher than normal.
A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the nucleus is larger than normal.

definition.value: Consider also annotating to 'increased nucleus:cytoplasm ratio' (FYPO:0006926).

label.value: abnormal protein export from nucleus during vegetative growth

value.value: A transport phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the export of protein from the nucleus is abnormal. Export of all proteins or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Encompasses both export of proteins normally retained in the nucleus and nuclear retention of normally exported proteins. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which spores have an abnormally low volume.

A cell morphology phenotype in which a spore has a larger volume than normal. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter are greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.
A cell phenotype characterized by altered spore morphology, i.e. the size, shape, or structure of the spore is abnormal.
A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the Golgi apparatus is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal Golgi organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal Golgi morphology.

label.value: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the actin cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology.

label.value: abnormal cell wall morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the fungal-type cell wall is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal cytoskeleton morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal cytoskeleton morphology.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of all or part of the endomembrane system is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal endomembrane system organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal endomembrane system morphology.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the endoplasmic reticulum is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal endoplasmic reticulum organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal endoplasmic reticulum morphology.
